ently treated lead vocals" with layered harmonies and tasteful guitars. That keeps the vocals front and story‑driven (my priority) while using tasteful ambient treatment and supporting harmonies rather than heavy multi‑tracking or over‑processing that would obscure phrasing.\n- Concise sequencing and arrangements: The album’s concise sequencing and arrangements match my preference for concise song structures that avoid indulgent instrumental detours and reward intentional, whole‑disc listening.\nWhy I reject the late‑’70s disco‑funk‑pop masterwork:\n- Singles/Hook focus versus narrative sequencing: Although it has attractive attributes (punchy warm mastering, a front‑and‑center vocal and Quincy Jones–style tight arranging), the description emphasizes bass‑first propulsion, hook‑heavy arranging, layered synths/strings and single edits that reward repeats and sing‑alongs. That signals a singles/hook orientation rather than the lyric‑forward, narrative sequencing I prize.\n- Production emphasis on groove and orchestration over intimate lyric focus: The disco/funk/pop masterwork’s bass-first propulsion, layered synths/strings and punchy percussion prioritize rhythmic drive and large-scale arrangements. Even with an intimate lead vocal, that production aesthetic risks placing groove and instrumental color ahead of the phrase‑forward, close‑miked intimacy I prefer and can lead to denser, less revealing midrange presentation.\n- Potential conflict with dislikes: The heavier layering of synths/strings and the single‑focused sequencing increase the chance of over‑processing or of mixes that emphasize hooks and instrumentation over clear, unambiguous vocal phrasing — exactly what I said I dislike.\nIn sum, while the late‑’70s disco‑funk‑pop masterwork has many admirable qualities (and an attractive front‑and‑center vocal), the tightly produced late‑’80s pop/R&B album aligns more closely and consistently with my core preferences for late‑’80s production values, lyric‑forward m