The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: From my self‑introduction I prioritize intimate, vocal‑forward recordings — close‑miked, breathy, tactile lead vocals with revealing midrange and modest compression; I like tight supporting harmonies that bolster but never bury a solo; I value restrained mastering that preserves headroom and transient detail, and arrangements that leave space for lyric‑centric storytelling. I explicitly dislike harmony‑first multitracking that buries the lead, over‑processed/glossy remasters, heavy limiting that smears transients, and production that obscures lyrical detail.
Candidate 2 most directly satisfies the core preferences. It explicitly offers a “tactile, breathy vocal presence,” which maps to my desire for close‑miked, micro‑dynamic lead vocals and phrase‑forward delivery. Although it’s “harmony‑forward” in character, the description adds that the three‑part blends “lift and color the lead without burying it,” matching my requirement for supporting harmonies that bolster rather than obscure the solo. The notes about “tasteful compression,” “roomy reverb,” and sequencing that emphasizes melodic clarity all point to production that preserves vocal detail and avoids heavy limiting or over‑polishing. Even the jangly midrange guitars and top‑end sheen can be acceptable here because the mix is framed around breathy lead presence and melodic clarity rather than dense, burying multitracks.
